                    </span><span class="tei-footnote-refs" dir="ltr" lang="en" xml:lang="en"><span class="tei-footnote-ref"><a href="#bib1625-1">1</a></span> </span></div><div style="margin:0 1em 1em; color: #999999;"><small><p><span class="srp-label"><strong>Syriaca.org URI</strong></span>: <span id="syriaca-id"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/1625">http://syriaca.org/person/1625</a></span></p></small></div></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="row"><div class="col-md-8"><div class="sources"><h3>Personal Information</h3><h4>Name variant(s): </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-person">
                        <span class="tei-persName"> Barhadbshabba </span>
                    </span>
                </span> <a href="/834-12" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Birth: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="spearLabel">Birth place: </span>
                                <span class="tei-persName">Barhadbshabba</span> was born in 
                                <span class="tei-placeName"> Syria</span> in the territory of 
                                <span class="tei-placeName">Ingila (Ingilene) </span> in the village of 
                                <span class="tei-placeName">Arʿa Rabtha</span>.
                             <a href="/834-16" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Sex: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">
                                    Barhadbshabba </span> was male. <a href="/834-13" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Place of residence: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Barhadbshabba</span> resided in <span class="tei-placeName">Asia</span>.
                             <a href="/834-27" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Sanctity: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Barhadbshabba</span> was a saint.  <a href="/834-15" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Barhadbshabba</span>
                                was a saint.
                             <a href="/834-35" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Occupation(s): </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Barhadbshabba</span> was a deacon.  <a href="/834-14" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Relationships</h3><p class="indent">
                            John of Ephesus 
                            commemorated
                            Barhadbshabba.
                         <a href="/834-39" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Events</h3><p class="indent">Abraham, Cyriac, Barhadbshabba, and
                                Sergius
                            abolished paganism, overthrew idolatry, uprooted altars, destroyed
                            shrines, and cut down trees in ardent religious zeal in the high
                            mountainous region of Asia.  <a href="/834-22" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Abraham, Cyriac, Barhadbshabba, and
                                Sergius
                            helped John of
                                Ephesus build ninety-two churches and ten monasteries in
                            four provinces with the help of the heavenly power.  <a href="/834-23" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">Abraham, Cyriac, Barhadbshabba, and
                                Sergius
                            were all buried together in the the sepulchre.
                         <a href="/834-29" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/></div><div class="citation"><h3>How to cite:</h3><span class="element">
